# Dune Analytics: complete platform architecture for QueryAgent design reference

**Dune Analytics operates as a dual-layered platform — a public marketing site and an authenticated SQL-powered analytics web application — built around three core content primitives: Queries, Visualizations, and Dashboards.** The platform supports **100+ blockchain networks**, hosts **700,000+ community dashboards** and **1.5M+ datasets**, and serves over 1 million users. Its architecture follows a community-first, fork-and-remix model where all content is public by default, creating a GitHub-like ecosystem for blockchain data. Understanding Dune's page structure, navigation hierarchy, and design patterns provides a detailed blueprint for QueryAgent's frontend planning.

---

## Platform architecture spans marketing, app, and documentation layers

Dune's frontend divides into three distinct layers, each with its own navigation, URL structure, and purpose:

**Marketing/product pages** (`dune.com/home`, `/enterprise`, `/pricing`, etc.) present the company's products and drive signups. These pages use a **dark-themed design** with animated WebM product graphics, customer story carousels, and social proof stats ("100+ Chains, 1M+ Users, 1.5M+ Datasets, AI Ready"). The homepage hero CTA drives users to `/discover/content/trending`.

**The authenticated web application** (`/discover`, `/library`, `/queries/{id}`, `/{username}/{dashboard-slug}`) is where analysts write SQL, build visualizations, and compose dashboards. This layer uses a **three-panel query editor**, a free-form dashboard builder, and a discover/browse system for finding community content.

**Documentation** (`docs.dune.com`) runs on Mintlify with an AI assistant, covering the Data Catalog, API Reference, SQL Query Engine, and learning resources. A separate docs site (`docs.sim.dune.com`) serves the real-time API product called Sim.

