## Navigation structure and information architecture

The **top navigation bar** in the marketing context contains a Product Switcher (Dune | Sim), dropdown menus for Products/Discover/Use Cases/Resources, a Pricing link, and auth CTAs. In the **authenticated app context**, it shifts to show Library, Discover, a global search bar (also triggered via **Cmd/Ctrl+P**), a Create menu (New Query, New Dashboard), an account/team context switcher, and the user avatar menu.

The **footer** organizes into four columns: Dune products (Data Hub through Pricing), Sim products (API through Pricing), Resources (Case Studies through Feedback), and Company (About through Merch). It also includes social links for LinkedIn, GitHub, X/Twitter, Discord, Telegram, and YouTube, plus legal links and system status.

**URL routing** follows clear patterns: static marketing pages use descriptive paths (`/pricing`, `/enterprise`), user-generated content uses `/{username}/{slug}`, queries use `/queries/{id}/{visualization_id}`, and discovery uses `/discover/content/trending` with query parameters for filters and tags.

The **content hierarchy** flows linearly: Users create **Queries** → Queries produce **Visualizations** → Visualizations populate **Dashboards**. Discovery hierarchy flows from Trending (4hr window) → Favorites (starred) → New → Tag-filtered → Advanced search.

