## Credit-based monetization and known UX challenges shape the competitive landscape

Dune's pricing uses a **credit-based compute model**: Small engine runs free (0 credits, manual only), Medium consumes credits from monthly allowance, and Large provides ~2x capacity. **Pay-as-you-go** charges $5.00 per 100 additional credits. The Free tier includes **2,500 monthly credits**, unlimited public dashboards, and API access. Plus ($399/mo) adds 10x credits, CSV exports, and removes watermarks. Premium ($999/mo) enables private queries and dashboards. Enterprise offers custom SLAs, white-labeling, and Datashare access.

Notable UX challenges relevant to QueryAgent's design include **SQL as a barrier** — Dune requires SQL knowledge, creating significant drop-off for non-technical users. **Week-1 retention sits at approximately 20%**, with a redesign target of 35%. The **credit system reportedly confuses users**. Query performance (slow/timed-out queries) remains the top complaint. Competitor Nansen V2 is noted as having better UI/UX for non-technical audiences. Dune's planned improvements for 2025+ include a **no-code drag-and-drop dashboard builder**, templates system, redesigned onboarding, and expanded AI conversational analytics (DuneAI).

